Cato did not live to see the conclusion of the war; he died in 149, at the age of 84 or 85 years, having retained his mental and physical vigour to the last He had two sons, one by his first wife, and one by his second wife, born when Cato was 80 years of age The elder sou, to whom many of Cato’s works were eddessen, died as praetor-elect, before his fatherl. · The other was grandfather of Cato Uticensis

The literary activity of the old censor was great, though his leisure was small ln Cicero's time a collection of 150 speeches was still extant The titles of about 90 are still known to us, and of some we possess a few fragments. Cato's greatest work, however, was his Origines, the first real historical work written in Latin. His predecessors had been merely compilers of chronicles. The work was founded on laborious investiga· tions, and comprised the history of Rome from the earliest times to 150 B.C.'‚ as well as notices of the history of other important Italian states. Further, Cato wrote of Agriculture, to which he was enthusiastically devoted. We still have his De re mattha, a collection of maxims loosely strung together. lle also composed works on law ; a sort of educational encyclopaedia for his son; and a collection of witty sayings (Δποφθέγματα) drawn from Greek as wellas Roman sources.

Plutarch seems to have known a collected edition of the pungent and proverbial utterances for which the censor was famous, and for which (not for any knowledge of philosophy) he received the title of sapr'ens (‘shrewd’) which he bore at the end of his life This edition was however not compiled hy Cato himself.

ln view of Cicero’s treatise, the Cato maior, it is necessary to say something of Cato's relations with the Greeks and Greek literature The ancients merely give us vague statements that he only began to learn Greek ‘in his old age '.
